The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Opto Circuits India Ltd will issue bonus shares in the ratio of 1:1, where one equity share will be issued for every one held. The issue is subject to shareholders? approval, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. The board has also recommended a dividend of Rs 4 on shares of Rs 10 each.

 SREI Infrastructure Finance Ltd has received Rs 3,000 crore of contract from NHAI to build roads on a build-operate-transfer basis. The projects will be completed over the next 18-36 months.

 Punj Lloyd has bagged a Rs 302-crore project from Road Infrastructure Development Company of Rajasthan to upgrade the Lalsot to Kota road.

 Tech Mahindra is planning to recruit 3,500 software engineers from various campuses in Gujarat. The company had recently opened its tenth development centre in Noida. 

 Panacea Biotec is collaborating with the National Research Development Corporation to produce and market the foot and mouth disease vaccine developed by Indian Veterinary Research Institute. 

 Parsvnath Developers has bagged the development rights from Chandigarh House Board for a 129-acre integrated residential-cum-commercial facility at the Rajiv Gandhi Chandigarh Technology Park. 

 Larsen and Toubro has opened its global headquarters in Mumbai. The office is part of L amp;T Infotech?s expansion plan, which includes the construction of six software development/ technology centres across the country. 

 Kurlon has launched a range of furnishing products, including curtains, upholsteries, bed sheets and towels. The prices of the curtains range between Rs 185 and Rs 606 per metre, and the towels are priced between Rs 100 and Rs 400.

 Telecordia Technologies has set up its Indian arm, Telecordia Technologies India Private Ltd, which will provide resources for mobile, fixed line and cable operators across the country. 

 UTI Bank has opened a branch at Jorhat in Assam. The bank has a network of 363 branches, 95 extension counters and 1,926 ATMs in India. 

 Paramount Pictures had chosen DHL as its official shipping and logistics partner for its motion picture Mission: Impossible III.

